<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38136c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38136c">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38136c"> 136(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bridge of / Alcantar </blockquote> <dd class="well"><mm class="note">Note: <cite>EB11</cite> &lsquo;Alca&aacute;ntara&rsquo;: a town of western Spain, in the province of C&aacute;ceres, situated on a rocky height on the left bank of the river Tagus, 7 m. from the Portuguese frontier. Pop. (1900) 3248. <mark>Alca&aacute;ntara (in Arab, &ldquo;the bridge&rdquo;)</mark> owes its name to the magnificent Roman bridge which spans the Tagus on the north-west. This was originally built about <year>A.D.</year> 105, in honour of the Roman emperor Trajan and at the cost of eleven Lusitanian communities. It is entirely constructed of granite blocks, without cement, and consists of six arches of various sizes, with a total length of 616 feet and a height of about 190 ft. in the middle piers, which are surmounted by a fortified gateway.</mm> </dd></dl>
